<li class="commentbody" id="comment-501227">
			<cite>Anna</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-501227" title="">December 20, 2010</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">56</div>

				<p>Growing up, I couldn&#8217;t stand this stuff&#8230;granted, my mom used to make it from the powdered mix. Bleh. Our sorority house cooks made some a few weeks ago and I tried it again and consequently fell madly in love! I literally just finished eating a bowl from my own batch from this recipe now that I&#8217;m home on winter break. It was really yummy! I used low-sodium beef stock and added more salt as needed (honestly it may even need more, but that&#8217;s a good thing, right?) I&#8217;m really intrigued by a former commenter&#8217;s use of mushroom stock. I also really loved how few pans were needed to make this and how I could clean up as I went&#8230;my parents certainly appreciate it, too.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-505946">
			<cite>sara</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-505946" title="">December 23, 2010</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">57</div>

				<p>So 4 years on I made this recipe tonight for St. Thorlac&#8217;s Day dinner (lunch) for my boyfriend and&#8211; he loved it!  I made it with coq au vin (Julia Child&#8217;s recipe, of course), brussels sprouts cooked in butter with shallots (I tried the new brussels sprouts/chestnuts recipe but apparently bought bad chestnuts) and made the heaven and hell cake from Saveur (sub raspberry mousse for peanut butter).  His first question was, &#8220;That&#8217;s not soup, is it?&#8221; (because he is notoriously not soup-friendly), followed shortly by &#8220;How&#8217;d you find a recipe for Flemish onion soup!?&#8221;  It was wonderful&#8211; thanks!</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-509328">
			<cite>julia</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-509328" title="">December 29, 2010</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">58</div>

				<p>how many does this serve?</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody highlighted" id="comment-515857">
			<cite><a href='http://smittenkitchen.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>deb</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-515857" title="">January 1, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">59</div>

				<p>It should serve 6.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-537992">
			<cite>beth</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-537992" title="">January 8, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">60</div>

				<p>I&#8217;ve tried a million recipes (Tyler Florence, Ina, GH) and this is by far the best and simplest!  Made it in a dutch oven, which had really even heat and let the onions carmelize really well.  Thanks for another great recipe!</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-543052">
			<cite>Alina</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-543052" title="">January 10, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">61</div>

				<p>I know this post is old, but I&#8217;m just discovering French cooking (and the need for soup on cold winter nights). Do you have any recommendations for the brand of white wine? And the cognac? I don&#8217;t have any alcohol at home&#8230;</p>
<p>Thank you for the recipe! I look forward to trying it out sometime this week!</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody highlighted" id="comment-543107">
			<cite><a href='http://smittenkitchen.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>deb</a></cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-543107" title="">January 10, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">62</div>

				<p>Alina &#8212; I don&#8217;t believe in using anything fancy to cook, no matter what TV chefs tell us. I use wine that is inexpensive but tastes passable. If you don&#8217;t want to splurge on Cognac, you can use brandy. Cognac is more or less &#8220;famous&#8221; brandy.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
<li class="commentbody" id="comment-556894">
			<cite>Adrianne</cite>
						&nbsp;
